WEBVTT

00:00:01.200 --> 00:00:03.520
<v Teacher><b>Comenzar</b>, what do you think that means?

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:05.760
<v Teacher><b>Comenzar</b>:

00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:06.720
<v Student><i>To commence.</i>

00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:08.400
<v Teacher><i>To commence.</i> Or?

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:09.600
<v Student><i>To start.</i>

00:00:09.340 --> 00:00:15.500
<v Teacher>Again this exists and you can use it and it’s probably easier because it sounds like commence so it’s easier to remember.

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:19.100
<v Teacher>But there’s another verb which is more common, which is <b>empezar</b>.

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:20.640
<v Teacher><b>Empezar</b>

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:23.920
<v Teacher>This is a <i>z</i> so that’s going to sound /<i>th</i>/ in Spain,

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:26.480
<v Teacher><b>empe/th/ar</b> in most of Spain.

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:27.920
<v Teacher><b>Empezar</b>.

00:00:27.920 --> 00:00:28.880
<v Student><b>Empezar.</b>

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:30.240
<v Teacher>Practice with this one for now.

00:00:30.240 --> 00:00:31.280
<v Teacher>This is <i>to start</i>.

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:33.280
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I start</i>?

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:35.120
<v Student><b>Empezo.</b>

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:37.339
<v Teacher>Good, that's what it should be, but what might happen?

00:00:37.339 --> 00:00:38.219
<v Student><b>Empiezo.</b>

00:00:38.219 --> 00:00:39.019
<v Teacher><b>Empiezo.</b>

00:00:39.019 --> 00:00:41.100
<v Teacher><i>He starts</i>:

00:00:41.180 --> 00:00:42.539
<v Student><b>Empieze.</b>

00:00:42.539 --> 00:00:45.339
<v Teacher>What must you do before you make that decision?

00:00:45.339 --> 00:00:47.339
<v Teacher>What must you do?

00:00:47.579 --> 00:00:49.739
<v Teacher>You must go back to the “to" form.

00:00:49.739 --> 00:00:51.660
<v Teacher>It's a very important habit.

00:00:51.980 --> 00:00:53.180
<v Student>It’s <b>empezar</b>.

00:00:54.140 --> 00:00:55.579
<v Student><b>Empeza.</b>

00:00:55.320 --> 00:00:55.960
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:55.960 --> 00:00:58.520
<v Teacher>And then what might be the next step after <b>empeza</b>?

00:00:58.520 --> 00:00:59.160
<v Student><b>Empieza.</b>

00:00:59.239 --> 00:01:00.040
<v Teacher><b>Empieza.</b>

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:02.280
<v Teacher>So this is the process we want to take.

00:01:02.280 --> 00:01:07.800
<v Teacher>It's essential for us to get into that habit of going back to the “to" form and then we know where we are.

00:01:07.800 --> 00:01:09.960
<v Teacher>Otherwise it's guesswork.

00:01:09.960 --> 00:01:12.020
<v Teacher><b>Empieza</b>: <b>empezar</b>-<b>empieza</b>. <i>They start</i>:

00:01:12.100 --> 00:01:13.100
<v Student><b>Empiezan.</b>

00:01:13.100 --> 00:01:13.940
<v Teacher><b>Empiezan.</b> Good.

00:01:13.940 --> 00:01:15.060
<v Teacher><i>You</i> (informal):

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:16.020
<v Student><b>Empiezas.</b>

00:01:16.020 --> 00:01:16.580
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:18.740
<v Teacher><i>When are you starting?</i>:

00:01:18.740 --> 00:01:20.100
<v Student>¿<b>Cuándo empiezas?</b>

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:21.860
<v Teacher>¿<b>Cuándo empiezas?</b> Very good.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.000
<v Teacher>So the E can split to IE.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:32.920
<v Teacher>That's something we need to know about the present and it's something we need to be on top of.

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:35.720
<v Teacher>Now it's in the present that this happens because as we know

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:41.260
<v Teacher>One of the fundamental elements of the present tense is to have that accent on the penultimate syllable.

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:45.900
<v Teacher>So it's having that accent on the penultimate syllable that makes that <i>e</i> vulnerable to splitting.

00:01:46.120 --> 00:01:51.160
<v Teacher>The <i>e</i> might split to <i>ie</i>, or the <i>o</i> might split to <i>ue</i>.

00:01:51.160 --> 00:01:57.700
<v Teacher>We know this already actually because we have <b>puedo</b>, and this is a split <i>o</i>.

00:01:57.700 --> 00:02:01.940
<v Teacher><i>To be able</i>, or "to can", of course there is no "to can" in English,

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:05.540
<v Teacher><i>to be able</i> we say is <b>poder</b>.
00:02:05.240 --> 00:02:08.200
<v Teacher>Here actually you can see closer that connection with <i>power</i>.

00:02:08.200 --> 00:02:11.880
<v Teacher>Before, I said that the word is related to the word <i>power</i> in English.

00:02:11.880 --> 00:02:13.240
<v Teacher>El poder

00:02:13.240 --> 00:02:14.600
<v Teacher><b>el</b> is the masculine <i>the</i>

00:02:14.920 --> 00:02:16.840
<v Teacher>we also saw it's the word for <i>he</i>,

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:18.900
<v Teacher>it's also the word for <i>the</i> for masculine words.

00:02:18.900 --> 00:02:21.380
<v Teacher><b>El poder</b> is <i>the power</i>.

00:02:21.380 --> 00:02:22.500
<v Teacher>So here it's a noun.

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:26.340
<v Teacher>It looks like a verb, but if it has <i>the</i> in front of it, we know it's a noun.

00:02:26.340 --> 00:02:28.740
<v Teacher><b>El poder</b> - <i>the power</i>.

00:02:28.740 --> 00:02:31.220
<v Teacher><b>Poder</b> - <i>to be able</i>.

00:02:31.560 --> 00:02:40.360
<v Teacher>When you take off your ending and you change it for present tense, and you stress that <i>o</i>, it splits into <i>ue</i>, and you get <b>puedo</b>.

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:46.060
<v Teacher>Again we can see the same phenomenon happening between words in English and Spanish.

00:02:46.060 --> 00:02:51.660
<v Teacher>So, for example, we have the word <i>port</i> in English, but we say <b>Puerto Rico</b>.

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:58.900
<v Teacher><b>Puerto Rico</b> means "the rich port". <b>Rico</b> means <i>rich</i> or <i>nice</i> or <i>tasty</i> or <i>sweet</i>.

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:02.660
<v Teacher>So <i>port</i> becomes <b>puerto</b>. We see the <i>o</i> splitting into <i>ue</i>.

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:06.740
<v Teacher>We have the word <i>force</i> in English,

00:03:06.740 --> 00:03:09.220
<v Teacher>in Spanish this is <b>fuerza</b>.

00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:10.900
<v Teacher>We have the word <i>school,</i>

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:13.860
<v Teacher>in Spanish this is <b>escuela</b>.

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:18.640
<v Teacher>We have <i>corp</i> in like <i>corporate</i>, which means <i>body</i>.

00:03:18.640 --> 00:03:21.280
<v Teacher>If <i>Corp</i> means <i>body</i> in <i>corporate</i>,

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:23.360
<v Teacher>how do you think it is in Spanish?

00:03:23.840 --> 00:03:24.720
<v Student><b>Cuerpo.</b>

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:25.840
<v Teacher><b>Cuerpo.</b>

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:26.800
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:26.800 --> 00:03:31.280
<v Teacher>We have <i>innovative</i>, and this <i>nov</i> in <i>innovative</i> means <i>new</i>.

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:33.840
<v Teacher>When you do something innovative, you do something new.

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:38.160
<v Teacher>And the word for <i>new</i> in Spanish is <b>nuevo</b>.

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:39.560
<v Teacher>So you saw the <i>o</i> splitting there.

00:03:39.560 --> 00:03:41.560
<v Teacher>You might have heard <b>pueblo</b> before.

00:03:41.560 --> 00:03:45.400
<v Teacher><b>Pueblo</b> means a <i>village</i> or a <i>people</i>.

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:46.760
<v Teacher><i>Population</i>

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:49.440
<v Teacher>in Spanish is one of these exceptions.

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:52.720
<v Teacher>It's not <b>populación</b>, it's <b>población</b>.

00:03:54.080 --> 00:03:55.680
<v Teacher>And you can see the connection between

00:03:56.140 --> 00:04:02.459
<v Teacher><b>población</b> and <b>pueblo</b>, which means <i>village</i> or <i>people</i>. <i>A people</i>.

00:04:02.459 --> 00:04:06.780
<v Teacher>You can see the <i>o</i> in <b>pob-</b> splitting into <i>ue</i> in <b>pueblo</b>.

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:10.400
<v Teacher><i>Mortgage</i>, by the way, actually means "death pact".

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:19.760
<v Teacher>You have <i>mort-</i>, which is the Latin root for <i>death</i>, and -<i>gage</i>, which means <i>pact</i>. The word for <i>dead</i> in Spanish is - have a guess.

00:04:20.299 --> 00:04:22.300
<v Student><b>Muerto</b> or <b>muerte</b>.

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:27.260
<v Teacher>Well actually, here, one you have the noun, <b>la muerte</b> is <i>the death</i>.

00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:29.660
<v Teacher>So the noun is the word you put <i>the</i> in front of.

00:04:29.660 --> 00:04:35.540
<v Teacher>In school they tell you that it's the thing, the object. But this is not an object.

00:04:35.699 --> 00:04:39.540
<v Teacher>We would think of it, we put <i>the</i> in front of it, it's a noun. <b>La muerte</b>.

00:04:39.540 --> 00:04:46.020
<v Teacher>But then the adjective, which is describing, it's <b>muerto</b> or <b>muerta</b>. Or <b>muertos</b> or <b>muertas</b>.

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:52.960
<v Teacher>So you can see in those words between English and Spanish this phenomenon of this <i>o</i> splitting into <i>ue</i> when it takes the stress.

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:55.280
<v Teacher>So this is useful for us for present tense.

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:57.360
<v Teacher>We need to know this for present tense

00:04:57.260 --> 00:05:03.900
<v Teacher>because if we have a verb like <b>dormir</b>, for example, that has an <i>o</i> in the root, when we stress it, it might split.

00:05:03.900 --> 00:05:06.380
<v Teacher>What do you think <b>dormir</b> means?

00:05:06.980 --> 00:05:09.220
<v Student><i>Staying still</i> or <i>dormant</i>?

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:11.460
<v Teacher>Yeah, what does <i>dormant</i> mean? A dormant volcano.

00:05:11.460 --> 00:05:15.620
<v Teacher>It actually means it's a sleeping volcano. Or <i>dormitory</i>, this is a nice connection to make as well.

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:21.620
<v Teacher>So <b>dormir</b> means <i>to sleep</i>.

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:23.379
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I sleep</i>?

00:05:23.699 --> 00:05:24.659
<v Student><b>Duermo.</b>

00:05:24.659 --> 00:05:25.379
<v Teacher><b>Duermo.</b>

00:05:25.379 --> 00:05:25.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:25.780 --> 00:05:30.020
<v Teacher>In Spanish if you want to say <i>I fall asleep</i>, you can say <i>I sleep myself</i>.

00:05:30.020 --> 00:05:31.940
<v Teacher>So how would that sound?

00:05:32.599 --> 00:05:34.120
<v Student><b>Me duermo.</b>

00:05:34.120 --> 00:05:37.879
<v Teacher><b>Me duermo.</b> Which means <i>I fall asleep</i>, rather than <b>duermo</b>, <i>I sleep</i>.

00:05:37.879 --> 00:05:40.120
<v Teacher>So you can say <i>I'm falling asleep</i>, <b>me duermo</b>.

00:05:40.120 --> 00:05:42.680
<v Teacher><i>It's so boring</i>, <b>me duermo</b>.

00:05:42.680 --> 00:05:44.120
<v Teacher><i>He sleeps</i>:

00:05:45.020 --> 00:05:45.979
<v Student><b>Duerme.</b>

00:05:45.979 --> 00:05:46.860
<v Teacher><b>Duerme.</b>

00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:47.340
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:47.340 --> 00:05:49.259
<v Teacher><i>They sleep</i>:

00:05:49.259 --> 00:05:50.220
<v Student><b>Duermen.</b>

00:05:50.220 --> 00:05:51.180
<v Teacher><b>Duermen.</b>

00:05:51.180 --> 00:05:53.659
<v Teacher>What do you think <b>encontrar</b> means?

00:05:53.659 --> 00:05:55.340
<v Teacher><b>Encontrar</b>:

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:57.200
<v Student><i>To encounter.</i>

00:05:57.200 --> 00:05:59.920
<v Teacher>Good. Which probably means:

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:00.640
<v Student><i>To meet.</i>

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:02.000
<v Teacher>Oh it does, it means that as well,

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.720
<v Teacher>but there's a more usual meaning as well.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:05.720
<v Student><i>To find</i>?

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:06.760
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:09.320
<v Teacher>So <i>I'm finding it</i> or <i>I find it</i>,

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:10.600
<v Teacher>how would you say that?

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:13.480
<v Student><b>Lo</b>,

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:16.040
<v Student>is it <b>encuentro</b>?

00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:17.080
<v Teacher>Yes it is.

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:19.240
<v Student><b>Lo encuentro.</b>

00:06:19.240 --> 00:06:20.680
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:24.280
<v Teacher>Something useful to bear in mind is that different versions of the verb,

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:31.760
<v Teacher>either the “to" form or some other version, might be the noun. So you mustn’t assume always that it's a verb. If you see <b>un encuentro</b>

00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:34.200
<v Teacher><i>an encounter</i>

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:35.800
<v Teacher>this is now a noun.

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:36.920
<v Teacher><i>An encounter</i>.

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:39.800
<v Teacher>Whatever we can put <i>a</i> or <i>the</i> in front of is a noun.

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:44.520
<v Teacher>So, many times some version of the verb will be the noun.

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:50.100
<v Teacher><b>Un encuentro</b> is <i>an encounter</i> but <b>encuentro</b>, <i>I encounter</i>.

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:53.220
<v Teacher><b>Demostrar</b> was <i>to demonstrate</i>, and if we get rid of this <i>de-</i>,

00:06:54.020 --> 00:06:56.420
<v Teacher>we get <b>mostrar</b> which means <i>to show</i>.

00:06:56.420 --> 00:06:57.540
<v Teacher><b>Mostrar</b>.

00:06:57.540 --> 00:06:59.700
<v Teacher>So how would you say: <i>I show</i>?

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:02.180
<v Student><b>Mostro.</b>

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:03.620
<v Teacher>It would be <b>mostro</b>-

00:07:03.620 --> 00:07:04.420
<v Student><b>Muestro</b>?

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:05.300
<v Teacher><b>Muestro.</b>

00:07:05.300 --> 00:07:05.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:06.740
<v Teacher><i>He shows</i>:

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:12.180
<v Student><b>Muestre</b>, wait. <b>Mostrar</b>. <b>Muestra</b>.

00:07:12.180 --> 00:07:13.300
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Muestra.</b>

00:07:13.300 --> 00:07:16.020
<v Teacher>We don't need to roll the r here because it's just one r.

00:07:16.020 --> 00:07:16.820
<v Teacher><b>Muestra</b>.

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:17.380
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:17.380 --> 00:07:21.620
<v Teacher>And <b>una muestra</b> actually is <i>a sample</i>.

00:07:21.539 --> 00:07:24.419
<v Teacher>So there is a noun there that shares that version.

00:07:24.419 --> 00:07:29.139
<v Teacher><b>Muestra</b>: <i>he shows, it shows, she shows, you</i> (formal) <i>show</i>.

00:07:29.139 --> 00:07:32.580
<v Teacher>But <b>una muestra </b>is <i>a sample</i>.

00:07:32.580 --> 00:07:33.539
<v Teacher><i>They show</i>:

00:07:35.080 --> 00:07:37.400
<v Student><b>Muestran.</b>

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:38.680
<v Teacher><b>Muestran.</b> Good.
